From Michael Covington Subject 'Easter' not derived from 'Ishtar' Several recent posts have identified the English word 'Easter' with the Babylonian goddess 'Ishtar' 'Easter' is a pagan word all right but it has nothing to do with If 'Easter' and 'Ishtar' were related their history would show But in Old English Easter was 'Eostre' cognate with English 'East' and German 'Ost' The reconstructed Proto Germanic form is 'Austron' Not until after did 'Easter' have a high front vowel like 'Ishtar' Clearly the two words have quite separate There may be neo pagans who worship Ishtar at Easter but if so they are making either a mistake of etymology or a deliberate play on Michael Covington linguistics Michael Covington Associate Research Scientist Artificial Intelligence Programs The University of Georgia phone Athens Georgia amateur radio